<p>No, itâ€™s not the 1,000 pound gorilla in the room we all make it out to be. Worse, the more we talk it up as the fundamental (or â€œinsurmountableâ€) barrier to new SaaS startups, the less inclined they are to get into the game: itâ€™s a self-fulfilling, dire prophesy. Truly itâ€™s more of an antiquated system ripe for <a href="http://www.codeforamerica.org/blog/2015/12/23/recapping-the-california-child-welfare-technology-vendor-forums-part-1/">small</a> hacks and <a href="https://18f.gsa.gov/rfpez/">simpler</a> interfaces. And those we are already starting to see. Instead the harder structural problem comes by way of a painful, rigid budgeting process and the need for <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/11/06/los-angeles-rolls-out-a-million-dollar-vc-fund-just-for-city-employees/">discretionary, innovation-friendly, on-demand reserves</a> to just. get. things. done.</p>

<ul>
  <li><em>Reframe</em>: Letâ€™s stop trying to fix procurement since it was a system built for â€œ<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3bK9B8_0FDQ">buying pencils</a>â€ and instead build <em>new interfaces and processes that are modern and startup-friendly from the start</em>.</li>
